frequent_values: HMI is seeking 375,000 in Speakers Initiative funding and 10,000 in Member Item Support for our Supportive Services Department, specifically to cover the salaries of our Counselors and Case Managers as we rise to meet a surge in demand for our services (now serving 2,500 young people, over triple our number 4 years ago). The increase in funding from the previous year (100,000) will be to cover all costs associated with hiring an additional Counselor, which will assist us in providing 500 additional young people this year with comprehensive mental health services. Services to be provided include: psychosocial Intake evaluation, individual and group counseling, hot meals (over 10,000 each year), homelessness pantry (clothing, food bags, hot showers, laundry services), family counseling, linkages to onsite HIV/STI/pregnancy testing, and complete wrap! -around support in the nations largest after-school program for LGBTQ youth.

The grant  will be used to support the NAACP NYC ACT-SO Academic Enrichment Program.  The Program is a free, year-long extracurricular youth development program targeted to African American high-school youth, which provides personalized mentoring, leadership training, and artistic, cultural, technological, and scientific skill development across 26 categories in the arts, humanities, and sciences. Funding will specifically support 2012-13 program expansion, outreach, recruitment, and retention activity and programming throughout the Metro New York area.  Operational goals are a 100 increase in student enrollment and retention; enhanced program content; increased capacity to deliver these services throughout New York City; and to increase public awareness and availability of these resources to high school students. The funds will be used in order t! o increase program and resource material support for student enrichment activities, from 250 to 500 students, by the end of FY 2013.

The funds requested will help to provide no-cost mammograms and clinical breast exams for economically disadvantaged, medically underserved women in the five boroughs of New York City.  They will also support outreach and education efforts that enable us to recruit women with cultural, linguistic, and geographic barriers to receigin annual screenings for breast cancer.

FUNDS WILL BE USED TO CREATE, DEVELOP AND PROMOTE CULTURAL, ARTISTIC, SPORTS AND GREENING EVENTS IN TEH PARK-WILLOW LAKE RESTORATION, BIRD BLINDS, CULTURAL EVENTS TO PROMOTE INTERCULTURAL COOPERATION AND USED TO PROMOTE THE PARK FOR ALL NEW YORKERS IN ALL FIVE BOROS
We will be using the funds to pay for the rent of our facilities. The Bridge to Life, Inc. is charged 1,500 a month for our Flushing office and material asistance space.

longest_value: Describe the program or services to be funded.: Educational and Cultural School Programs for students k-12 grades. Currently we offer five cross-disciplinary programs:The Legend of the Spider, Carnevale in Venice, Life in Ancient Rome, Puppetry and Literature and Guided Historical Tours. All programs culminate in a hands-on project to take home (except the Guided Historical Tour).Speakers Bureau Programs: the purpose of the Speakers Bureau Program is to make programs related to Italian heritage and culture available to schools, community groups, senior and civic associations at their preferred sites or here at the museum. Our experienced speakers can cover twenty topics. On-Site Exhibitions: the museum presents s new temporary exhibition every three or four months, and maintains three permanent exhibits.All programs are based on the promotion of Italian-American culture.Terza Domenica Heritage Series: these are special educational lectures, films, displays or demonstrations usually offered on the third Sunday of the each month at the museum. Most of these programs have accompanied educational materials for guest, such as bookmarks, pamphlets and posters.Italian Language Classes for adults are offered two semesters a year, 15 weeks at a time. Courses offered: Introduction to Italian Language, History and Culture I and II, Journey through Italian Language, History and Culture, Italian for Beginners, Italian II, Italian III, Intermediate Conversation through Literature, Communicative Italian I and II, Italian Theater and Literature.

AUDITIONS  BEGINNERS: In 2012-13, Ballet Tech will audition 30,000 2nd-5th graders at 200 public schools across NYC. Ballet Tech will also hold 6 auditions at its studios. No experience is required to audition. Roughly 400 3rd-5th graders will enroll in Ballet Techâ€™s Beginner Program and take weekly dance classes for up to 12 weeks. Beginners learn the fundamentals of ballet: basic steps, simple combinations and vocabulary. In the fall of 2013, 40 graduates of the Beginner Program will enroll full-time at the New York City Public School for Dance. NYCPSD: A joint venture with the NYC DOE, NYCPSD integrates a rigorous academic curriculum with pre-professional ballet training for 150 students in grades 4-8. Students study academics and dance at Ballet Techâ€™s facilities. The DOE provides academic faculty and staff. Ballet Tech provides ballet tra! ining and dancewear. Students take up to 12 weekly classes including ballet technique, pointe, menâ€™s, repertory, character, modern, and stretch.

The OPEN ACCESS PROGRAMâ€”which receives applications from over 700 artists annuallyâ€”ensures that our programming reflects the diversity of NYC and the globe.  Lark is one of a handful of theaters nationally that reviews every script that is submitted.  Additionally, we reach out to university and organizational partners to identify voices that are underrepresented in American theaterâ€”and American society at largeâ€”including those from Middle Eastern, South Asian and African Diasporas as well as Latino, African American, Asian American and Native American communities.  Artists are consideredâ€”through a â€œblindâ€ process, in which information about the author is not known by evaluatorsâ€”for inclusion in Playwrightsâ€! ™ Week (a festival of 8-10 plays where the general public attends for free) and other programs including fellowships, workshops, and residencies.

Through the Healthy Bronx Initiative House Visit program jointly run by CIR, CIR-PEI, and Bronx Lebanon Hospital Centerâ€™s Family Medicine Department, we study the correlation between housing stock and poor health and provided education and resources to at-risk tenants.  This funding would allow us to expand the program to hire a full-time Health and Housing Community Health Worker (CHW) who will be assigned to substandard housing units whose patients suffer from chronic conditions like HIV, HBPC, high blood pressure management, heart conditions, and asthma.  The Health and Housing CHW would create an ongoing relationship with these patients, referring them not only to resources for their health problems but also education and resources to ameliorate housing conditions that may be negatively impacting their health.  This is a pilot project to eva! luate whether a dual focus on health and housing yields additional quality and savings.  (Salary, benefits, training and administrative costs.)

The RHEDC proposes to beautify, uplift, and enhance the densely populated Richmond Hill community by running holiday/festival lights on either side of the primary traffic thoroughfare stretching from Lefferts Boulevard to Van-Wyck Expressway, October - January of each yearâ€”the cold, gray months when days are short and shoppers are more inclined to stay indoors.  In addition, decorative streamers/festival banners will be strung along Liberty Avenue, from Lefferts Boulevard to Woodhaven Boulevard, in the same time period (October - January).  These festive, decorative lights and streamers will generate cheer and good feeling in the community, encourage shoppers to linger in shops, and promote holiday business. The collaborative effort of community merchants to steer and execute this festival-spirit project will promote team spirit and business coo! peration.  A collective of community merchants will contribute funds to offset some of the costs of this project; along with other civic groups
